  "text": "In 2009, Bernatsky et al. [CITATION_1] investigated the history of an abnormal pap test by self-administrated questionnaire in a Canadian multicentre cohort of 320 SSc women. The lifetime prevalence of an abnormal pap test was 25.4%, compared to 13.8% reported in the Canadian general population; moreover, a significant positive association with diffuse skin subset, smoking history, and younger age was noted. Even if a detection bias could influence these findings (SSc patients may be more likely to be aware of comorbidities than general population), authors concluded that it seems prudent to ensure adequate attention to cervical cancer screening for SSc women.",
